"""
Auto-generated version info. BUILD_NUMBER is incremented by pre-commit hook.
CHANGELOG is populated from recent git log entries.
"""

VERSION = "0.1.2"
BUILD_NUMBER = 259
# NOTE: Keep this list short (~8 entries). Remove old ones as new ones land.
CHANGELOG = [
    "Universal visited-feature loop fix at the harness level. Beregond's HP chart on the report site flagged a stairs_up + blacksmith oscillation (996 + 988 turns) -- same loop class as the chest + pool ones, just two-tile. Every feature-room mode re-fires its prompt every time the player steps onto the tile, and the wayfinder routes through visited features as walkable transit, so each pass burns turns the policy then has to 'back' out of. Added a step()-level guard: when the agent JUST LANDED (position changed this step) on a tile already in visited_features AND the resulting mode is loop-prone (altar/pool/garden/library/oracle/chest/tomb/vendor/blacksmith/shrine/stairs_up/alchemist/war_room/taxidermist/fey_garden -- stairs_down intentionally excluded), reset gs.prompt_cntl back to game_loop so the feature tile is pass-through. The just_landed gate is critical: same-tile steps (e.g., 'pray' inside an altar_mode dialog) DON'T trigger the override, so first-time boon-claiming stays intact. 60-run grid (20 seeds × 3 races × 3000T): alive 26 -> 21 (more honest -- 5 fake survivals dropped), MAX FLOOR F8 -> F9 (matches project record), MAX LEVEL holds at L7, mean floor 3.67 -> 3.82, Lv5+ count 11 -> 9 (slight drop), Lv6+ count 4 -> 5 (new project high), Lv7+ count 1 (Fili the dwarf F8 L7 with 80 kills). The chest + pool single-site fixes from the prior commit stay but are now redundant with the universal guard -- left in for defense-in-depth.",
    "Unstick the fake-survival 'alive' agents. The HP-over-the-run charts on the playtest report site showed dozens of 'alive' agents flatlining their HP from T300 to T3000 -- the agent was alive only because it was stuck in an infinite loop, not because it was playing. Two distinct loops surfaced. (1) CHEST GAME BUG: the chest handler at process_chest_action doesn't accept 'l' as a leave command (only o / i / n / s / e / w). The smart policy's chest-mode return value was 'l' on the 15% leave roll AND on my new HP<40+no-pot safety gate, which logged 'Invalid command' and stayed in chest_mode for 2900+ turns sending 'l' repeatedly. Fix: the policy's chest-mode walk-away now picks a cardinal direction that's not a wall. ACTION_HINTS line corrected to reflect reality. (2) POOL ANTI-BACKTRACK: visited pool tiles stay walkable in BFS transit, so the wayfinder routed THROUGH a pool to reach a target, the HP<50 gate walked away, and BFS routed back through the same pool from the neighbour. seed=200 elf burned 2925 turns oscillating e/w through one pool tile at HP 1/28. Added the recent_step_set anti-backtrack pattern to pool walk-away (same fix shape as the wayfinder + chest now). 60-run grid (20 seeds × 3 races × 3000T): mean floor 3.33 -> 3.67 (+0.34), mean level 2.83 -> 3.02 (crossed Lv3 mean for the first time), max floor F7 -> F8, Lv5+ count 7 -> 11, Lv4+ 19 -> 21, suspect 'alive but barely moved' count 8 -> 4 (the 4 remaining are vendor-shop re-entry loops, parked for a follow-up).",
    "Depth pass: vendor stockpile bumped + narrow chest-explosion safety net. The L4+ death audit showed two killable patterns alongside the legit-deaths cluster: (1) starvation finishing off long-kill runs (107-kill agent dying hungry at F4) and (2) chest explosions one-shotting low-HP agents with no heal pot in the bag. Bumped vendor STOCK targets: potion_healing 3 -> 4, food 12 -> 15, potion_mana 2 -> 3 (covers one extra emergency per floor on 6-8 floor runs). Added a narrow chest-mode gate: skip the open when HP < 40 raw AND heal_pot_slot is None -- preserves the 85% open rate for all healthy / has-fallback states. 60-run grid (20 seeds × 3 races × 3000T): alive 29/60 -> 41/60 (+41%), max floor F6 -> F9 (new record), max level L6 -> L7 (new record), Lv7+ count 0 -> 1 (Oin the dwarf, F9 L7 with 111 kills, dead to UNDEAD DRAGON at T856). Starvation deaths halved 4 -> 2, chest deaths halved 2 -> 1. Mean floor dropped slightly (3.27 -> 3.03) because more agents now survive at moderate depth instead of dying deep, but the top-of-distribution shifted dramatically upward.",
    "XP per kill scales quadratically with monster level: (L+1)*8 + L^2 * 2. The prior linear (L+1)*8 underpaid for deep-floor kills -- a Lv5 Wraith is ~80x more dangerous than a Lv0 Goblin but the linear formula only gave 6x the XP. New curve keeps Lv0 monsters at 8 XP (early game unchanged) but a Lv5 monster now gives 98 XP (was 48), a Lv8 gives 200 (was 72). The quadratic ramp scales rewards with risk. 60-run grid (20 seeds × 3 races × 3000 turns): max level 5 -> 6 (Balin the dwarf, F5 L6 with 151 kills -- new record), Lv5+ count jumps from 1 to 5, Lv4+ from 4 to 13, Lv3+ from 12 to 31 (~half the grid). Mean floor 3.30 -> 3.27 (essentially flat), mean kills 47 -> 46. The 'XP economy as the depth wall' framing was correct -- bumping linear yield helped, but quadratic-with-difficulty is the right shape for a roguelike where deep monsters are far more threatening than shallow ones.",
    "XP per kill bumped (active_monster.level + 1) * 5 -> * 8 across all four kill sites in combat.py. Death-cause + waste% audits identified character-power-at-depth as the depth ceiling: agents reached F4-F8 in 500-800 turns but at Lv2-3, which left them one wraith hit from death. The +60% XP yield accelerates level climbs without changing fight dynamics -- monsters still hit the same, the agent just grows faster between fights. Deep grid (30 runs, 3000 turns) after the change: alive 9 -> 15 (+67%), max level 4 -> 5 (new record), Lv3+ count 8 -> 12, Lv4+ 0 -> 4, Lv5+ 0 -> 1. Top run is Beregond the human, F8 alive at Lv5 with 128 kills. The XP economy was the real wall.",
    "Deploy reports to main:docs/playtest/ instead of a gh-pages branch. dachhack/LegendOfZot already serves GitHub Pages from main:docs/ (the spell-sprite-audit site); pushing to a parallel gh-pages branch left the playtest reports invisible. Refactored deploy_gh_pages() to use nested-tree manipulation via git plumbing -- ls-tree walks down docs/playtest, hash-object stages new report blobs, mktree rebuilds the tree leaf-up (docs/playtest -> docs -> root), commit-tree + push commit to main. Stays additive: prior reports + non-docs files preserved by the parent-tree merge. Companion change on main: .github/workflows/build-android.yml gets paths-ignore: ['docs/**'] so docs-only deploys skip the APK build. Reports now live at https://dachhack.github.io/LegendOfZot/playtest/ as a sibling of the existing audit pages.",
    "Depth pass: tile-coverage descent gate + vendor-each-floor + food economy. Four coordinated changes from the waste% audit. (1) PlaytestSession tracks visited_tiles_this_floor (reset on descent); obs.tile_coverage exposes {visited, walkable, pct}. The smart policy gains a high_coverage_descend gate at coverage_pct >= 80 + D reachable + not is_weak that promotes D to tier 0 -- mostly dormant in practice (agents typically descend at 20-50% coverage via incidental D-stepping) but catches the long-tail floors where the agent would otherwise patrol-bounce for 100+ turns chasing a far beneficial. (2) V folded into unvisited_beneficials_exist so the descent gate doesn't release until the floor's vendor (if any) is visited -- 'vendor on every floor' guarantee. V stays in its own priority tier (after SAFE) so it doesn't add detour cost on close-beneficial routing. (3) Food economy: vendor stockpile target 8 -> 12 Rations (~480 nutrition vs prior 320), eat-when-hungry trigger 50 -> 70 (avoid the starvation HP-tick band), MEAT_EAT_BEFORE 8 -> 20 (eat raw meat earlier so kill drops actually convert before rotting). (4) Lantern timing kept at original (periodic-when-very-stuck firing helps long sweeps -- the tightened version dropped F8 reach in the smoke). Deep grid (30 runs, 2000 turns): mean floor 3.53 -> 3.83, Lv3+ count 5 -> 8 (DOUBLED), max floor F8 still held (waste% bias toward depth at the cost of some survival).",
    "Tier-routing the wayfinder + movement waste% in reports. Per-floor revisit tracking landed in playtest_report.py (every game_loop step where (x,y) changes is classified as first_visit or revisit; revisit/total = waste%) and surfaced 47% waste on a strong F5 L4 154-kill run -- agents were walking to a far chest before a near garden because the priority list was rank-ordered, not distance-ordered. The wayfinder now uses a tiered priority: each tier is a tuple of feature types competing on BFS path_dist, tiers iterate in order. BENEFICIAL_SAFE rooms are all in tier 0 -- the closest reachable beneficial wins, not the alphabetically-first one. Same pattern for the wants_vendor / ready_to_clear / unvisited_beneficials_exist branches. Deep grid (30 runs, 2000 turns): mean waste 47% -> 35.7% (-24% relative), alive 13 -> 17, max floor F9 ALIVE (new record, Finrod the elf at 125 kills with only 25.7% waste). High-waste runs now correlate cleanly with starvation deaths (Kili dwarves at 56-78% waste died at F4 L3-4 after 111-123 kills -- the patrol-bouncing burned the food clock), suggesting waste% is also the right proxy for the depth-deeper-but-hungry deaths.",
    "Playtest report site: per-run HTML hero pages + GitHub Pages deploy. New wizardscavern/playtest_report.py module collects per-turn data during a smart-policy run (HP timeline, kills by floor + monster, vendor purchases, identifies, descents, equipment swaps, last 60 log lines, last 12 actions) and renders a standalone HTML page per hero. The page covers: hero name + race + outcome banner (SURVIVED / FELL), final tally (turns, max floor, level, HP, mana, gold, kills, buys, identifies), HP timeline SVG chart across the run, equipment + inventory snapshot, journey ledger (descents + kills-by-floor + top victims + purchases table), and a death scene block (cause, last 30 log lines, last actions) when the hero dies. Reads gs.log_lines directly each turn so it doesn't lose lines to the in-game 16-cap rotation (the obs.log delta misses lines under burst output). Two CLI flags on playtest_harness: --report-dir DIR writes <slug>.html + <slug>.json + regenerates index.html (sorted by max floor desc, then level desc); --deploy adds a worktree-based push of the report directory onto a gh-pages branch (idempotent + additive -- each run appends to the existing site rather than replacing). .gitignore now excludes playtest_reports/. Smoke (5 seeds × 3 races at 2000 turns): 15 hero pages generated + index, kills logged correctly per hero (top run: Halbarad the human, F5 L4, 154 kills, alive @ 2000T). The previously-reported 'mean 0.7 kills/run' across the deep grid was an artifact of the broken log delta -- real kill counts are 30-150+ per run.",
    "Deeper pass: opportunistic M-hunting, pre-combat buffs, aggressive casting. The audit caught mean kills/run = 0.5 across 30 runs of 5000 turns -- agents barely fought because M wasn't in the priority list when boons remained, and the BFS routes AROUND M tiles (they're in BLOCK_TRANSIT). So an agent could grab boons -> descend -> repeat for the entire budget without leveling once. Three changes: (1) M slotted into all healthy-state priority lists right after V (boons_remain: SAFE + V + M + T + N; ready_to_clear: SAFE + V + M + T + N + D; else: D + V + M + T + N + SAFE). Agent now banks opportunistic XP on the way to chests / gardens / vendors. (2) Pre-combat buff drink in game_loop: when M is adjacent AND we have an identified buff potion (strength/defense/stone_skin/regeneration/berserker/etc.) AND HP >= 60%, open inventory to drink BEFORE stepping into combat. Buff potions have 3-5 turn durations and were being wasted drunk far from fights; now they time to the actual encounter. (3) Damage spell cast rate bumped 0.65 -> 0.90 in combat_mode. Spells beat melee (more dmg/turn, no durability loss); mana regens at 1/5 moves so casting freely between fights is sustainable. Deep grid (30 runs, 5000 turns): alive 13 -> 16, mean floor 3.2 -> 3.5, mean kills 0.5 -> 0.7 (+40%), F1-stuck cluster 19 -> 1. Max floor F9 still held; level climb mean 1.6 -> 1.7.",
    "F4 cliff pass: magical items + scroll/buff use + undead-aware threat. 30-run audit reading gs.log_lines directly (the obs.log delta misses lines on buffer rotation) caught two wins and one big leak. WINS: vendor purchases were always working (85 items bought across the grid, properly logged as 'You bought Mace for 60 gold' etc.) -- the prior 'zero buys' reading was an audit regex bug, not a policy bug. LEAK: the policy bought potion_healing / potion_mana / food / lantern_fuel / weapon / armor but COMPLETELY SKIPPED magical items: 0 spell scrolls, 0 stat potions, 0 utility scrolls. Expanded the vendor buy list: one of each unknown potion_<type> beyond healing/mana (Strength Elixir / Defense Brew / Stone Skin / Regeneration / Berserker / Fire Resistance / etc.) and up to 3 scrolls (mapping reveals floor, upgrade buffs gear, spell_scroll teaches a spell, remove_curse breaks welds). Reserve raised to 150g for emergency healing-pot restock. Surfaced scroll_type + potion_type in _inventory_obs so the usage policy can target effects. Inventory branch now reads SAFE identified scrolls (mapping/upgrade/spell/lantern_upgrade/restoration/foresight/protection/identify/vendor_restock; skips teleport/descent which can land badly) and drinks identified buff potions (strength/defense/stone_skin/regeneration/berserker/etc.) when HP < 95%. F4 audit identified UNDEAD WRAITHs as the killer (5/12 F4 deaths); added a two-band threat assessment in combat_mode: general monsters still flee at m.level > pc+2, but undead (wraith/lich/skeleton/vampire/ghost/zombie/spectral/phantom) flee one tier earlier (m.level > pc.level), since they hit raw and drop no meat. Deep grid (30 runs, 5000 turns): alive 12 -> 13, mean floor steady ~3.2, MAX FLOOR F8 -> F9 (new record), F4 deaths 13 -> 8, F4 wraith deaths 5 -> 2. Magical items now flow: 17 scrolls bought / 6 stat potions / 5 resistance potions across the grid, all consumed via the usage policy.",
    "Combat-balance pass: vendor upgrade-buy + pool HP gate. Instrumented 30-run audit revealed two big leaks. (1) Vendors stocked Longsword (atk+10) / Mace (+6) / Morningstar (+8) and Ring Mail (def+4) / Chainmail (+6) but the policy only bought stockpile (potions/food/mana) -- agents walked past upgrades for 60 vendor visits, then died at F4 holding a Dagger (atk+2). _vendor_obs now surfaces attack_bonus / defense_bonus / buc_status / is_sealed on weapon/armor, and the vendor policy buys any strict-bonus upgrade affordable above a 150g healing-pot reserve, skipping known-cursed / sealed items. (2) Pool drinks were a hidden death cliff: cursed pools deal 20-35 no-defense damage and gold pool 'mimic' outcome 50-100 raw -- 4/23 deaths in the prior audit had 'basin drains empty' as the last log line. The smart_policy 'dr' was unconditional; now gated by hp >= 50 with walk-away fallback. Two healthy effects: agents skip lethal drinks at low HP, and the policy now actively shops upgrades. Deep grid (30 runs, 5000 turns): alive 6 -> 12 (doubled), max floor 6 -> 8 (new record, seed=5678 human F8), max level 3 -> 4 (Lv4+ count 0 -> 2), F4 deaths 13 -> 10. The user-flagged 'identifying and using items and buying upgraded equipment from vendors' is now consistently exercised (167 Minor Heal + 41 Heal uses, 46 equip swaps across the grid; vendor identify scrolls runs ~15/grid).",
    "Picker rooms wired: oracle (O), alchemist (Q), war room (K), taxidermist (X). The handoff and playtester both flagged these as unclaimed boons sitting on every floor -- the agent walked onto them, mode-prompted, and the policy's catch-all 'back' bounced out without claiming the boon. Now each gets a proper dispatch in step() + a smart_policy handler: (O) skip the gaze (hints are text-only, useless to our policy); (Q) combine 2 potions when alch_uses > 0 and bag has >=2 potions (send 'c' then '1 2'; 90% gives a stronger combined potion, 10% botch sits inert because we only auto-drink potion_healing); (K) send '1' for free intel which reveals all special rooms on the NEXT floor (huge value -- pre-scouts the descent); skip the 100+f*5g raid mode gamble. (X) sell trophies for gold when the bag holds any. BENEFICIAL_SAFE expanded from (C,G,L,O,A,P) to (...,Q,K,B,F) so the wayfinder PROACTIVELY targets these rooms (X stays opportunistic since it needs trophies). _feature_paths_obs widened from 10 -> 15 target types. Smoke (30 runs, 5000 turns): mean max floor 3.3 -> 3.5, F4 reached by 13 agents (was 10) -- war room intel + alchemist combine pull agents deeper, faster. Q/K/X gate on floors 10-45 / 20-50 / 10-45 per their docstrings so most current-budget runs never see them; the wiring matters for the depth runs that will.",
    "Deep-run pass: anti-backtrack guard + cursed-gear-aware swap + always-hunt in ready_to_clear. 5000-turn deep grids surfaced two new loop classes that the BFS pathfinder unmasked: (1) seed=42 dwarf F2 burned 4857/5000 turns alternating n/s in a 2-tile corridor -- the SE-tiebreak in frontier_step was flipping direction each turn because each side's BFS picks the other side as the SE-most frontier. PlaytestSession now tracks the last 4 (z,x,y) positions and surfaces `recent_step_set` in obs; the policy's _swap_if_backtrack wrapper redirects BFS first_steps that would re-step a recent tile to a non-recent walkable alternative. (2) seed=42 dwarf with cursed+sealed+broken Specter's Touch equipped (welded to hand) burned 1568 i->e1->x cycles trying to swap to the Battleaxe in slot 1 -- the game refuses to unequip cursed gear. Added cursed_weapon / cursed_armor flags from buc_known+buc_status, gated both the game_loop pre-inventory swap trigger AND the inventory branch swap blocks AND the _best_upgrade detection on those flags. Also restored M-before-D unconditionally in ready_to_clear (boon-exhaustion gate) so the agent hunts when pressing instead of fleeing -- the user's framing: hunger / fuel pressure should push TOWARD efficient monster clearing for meat/XP/gold, not toward descent. Deep grid (30 runs, 5000 turns): mean max floor jumped 2.6 -> 3.3, Lv3+ count 2 -> 5, max level ever reached climbs from 3 to 4 for the first time, max floor F7 holds. Alive count drops 22 -> 7 because the prior 'alive' pool included zombie-loopers (oscillating corridors, inventory cycles, broken weapon stuck) that were burning the budget without progress -- those agents now correctly engage and die at deeper floors. Honest deaths, per the handoff rubric.",
    "Smart playtest policy: inventory branch elif-cascade short-circuit fix. Playtester subagent found that when the equipped weapon is broken AND no working replacement exists in inventory, the broken-weapon elif block was entered, found no swap candidate, left `proposed = None`, and the cascading `elif`s for armor / upgrade / eat-when-hungry were all skipped. Result: dwarf seed=314 stood on tile (8,11) at hunger=49 with food in slot 9 for 1738 consecutive turns, bouncing i -> x -> i -> x while the game_loop hunger trigger kept re-opening inventory. Converted the elif-chain to sequential `if proposed is None` guards so a branch that ENTERS but finds no candidate falls through to later steps. Smoke (30 runs, 2000 turns): seed=9001 dwarf flipped from died-T568 to alive at 2000 (the broken-weapon-no-replacement victim), and the inventory mode-time dropped to ~2% on other runs (was inflated by the dwarf:314 bug alone).",
    "Smart playtest policy: 'ready to clear' replaces 'is_strong'. The level-gated hunt-mode (Lv>=3 + HP>=70% + non-broken weapon) from the BFS pathfinder commit never fired -- a chicken-and-egg trap, agents couldn't reach Lv3 without hunting and couldn't hunt without Lv3. Redefined the gate around how a real player actually plays a floor: get every reachable boon (chest/garden/altar/pool/library/oracle) FIRST, then settle in to efficiently clear monsters for meat + XP + gold, then descend. ready_to_clear fires when (a) feature_paths shows no more reachable beneficials on this floor, OR (b) resource pressure forces the issue (hunger < 60 OR fuel_total < 15 lantern fires) AND (c) the agent isn't is_weak (broken gear / low HP recovers first). When ready_to_clear, M slots into priority BEFORE D so the agent gathers kill-drop value on the way to the stairs. The fuel gauge correctly accounts for spare canisters as +10 each (matches the auto-refill mechanic). Smoke (30-run grid, 2000 turns): 22/30 alive, mean floor still ~2.7, but NOW 2/30 reach Lv3 (was 0/30 with level-gate) and a seed=271 elf pushes to F7 before dying. The XP / level climb gate is unblocked.",
    "Smart playtest policy gets real pathfinding. Replaced the greedy Manhattan walker (step toward larger-axis delta with 30% wall-escape jitter) with BFS over the player's reachable set on the current floor, treating walls + undiscovered tiles + M/W hazards as transit blockers. Three new obs fields in wizardscavern/playtest_harness.py: (1) `feature_paths[type]` -> `{first_step, path_dist}` per D/V/C/G/A/L/O/P/T/N, replacing nearest_features' Manhattan vectors with actually-reachable distances; (2) `frontier_step` -> BFS first-step toward the nearest discovered tile with an undiscovered cardinal neighbour, lower-right tiebreak (max x+y wins ties) so the agent drifts SE the way a real player hunts for D; (3) `nearest_monster_path` -> BFS to a cardinal neighbour of the closest visible M, plus the step into the M, used by hunt-mode. Smart policy distant wayfinder + frontier walker now consume BFS first_step instead of greedy-axis steps. stairs_down_mode handler ported to feature_paths with path_dist<=3 gate, fixing the seed=13 human stairs ping-pong (was 10 stairs_down_mode entries in 40 turns, now 3 clean descents over 2000 turns). Smoke (30-run grid, 2000 turns): 23/30 alive (was 18/30), mean floor 2.7 (was ~2.0), seed=13 human went from died-F4-T648 to alive-F6-T2000.",
    "Weaker per-floor scaling for tomb-adjacent undead guardians. Death-cause analysis (30 runs, 2000 turns) showed Wraith / Lich / Skeleton / Vampire variants drove 12/24 deaths with 6/24 killing blows exceeding 40 HP -- one-shot territory for fresh characters whose max HP starts at 28/30/64 by race. Prior scaling spawned at `target_lvl = player.z + 1` with pool reach +1 above that, so F3 wraiths hit Lv5; the spawn cap (player.z + 2) didn't fully tame the curve. Dropped the +1 boost: tomb-adjacent undead now scale 1:1 with floor (`target_lvl = player.z`), pool `[z-1, z+1]`, spawn cap `min(template+1, z+1)`. F1 wraiths cap at Lv1, F3 at Lv3, F8 still at Lv8. Rewards player STR / HP investment in tomb fights instead of overwhelming Lv1 explorers at depth. Re-run: killing-blows >40 HP collapsed 6/24 -> 1/23, max blow 62 -> 50, kills now distribute across Lv2-5 instead of clustering at Lv4-5. Mean floors up across all races (elf 2.7 -> 3.4, human 3.2 -> 3.5, dwarf 3.1 -> 3.0). Total deaths similar (24 -> 26) because each individual encounter is more survivable but agents push deeper and die at the next wall -- which is the right shape for a roguelike.",
    "Two food-economy fixes surfaced by the latest playtest pass. (1) `get_monster_meat_info` in items.py:2734 was treating any monster whose name CONTAINED a non-edible keyword as inedible -- the substring 'lich' inside 'Lichen' was matching the undead-Lich key (mapped to None) and returning 'inedible' for what should be a foragable plant/fungal creature. Same trap could fire for any short keyword that's a prefix of an unrelated name. Replaced both substring loops (MEAT_COOK_STYLES key match + non_edible_keywords scan) with word-boundary regex (`\\bkw\\b`), so 'Lichen' is now correctly edible while 'Lich', 'Death Lich', 'Death Knight', 'Mold Beast', 'Vampire Bat' all keep their correct classification (verified end-to-end). Lichens were ~17% of the playtest's wasted starvation engagements -- this single fix recovers them. (2) Starter pack Rations bumped 3 -> 5 (vendor.py:113 + harness mirror). Prior playtest: 10/30 runs died before reaching a vendor with 0 food in the bag. 5 Rations = 200 nutrition uses, ~doubles the pre-vendor cushion. Smoke (30 runs, 2000 turns): mean floor up across all races (elf 2.7, human 3.2, dwarf 3.1 vs prior 1.7-1.85), human alive 2->3, dwarf mean turns 1002->1066, max floor steady at 6.",
    "Smart playtest policy: edibility-aware starvation logic. Prior pass surfaced a sub-issue: of 39 starvation-override engagements, only 2 (5.1%) produced meat -- the agent fought Wraiths, Liches, Lichen, Golems with no meat return because obs.monster doesn't expose edibility. Four coordinated fixes in wizardscavern/playtest_harness.py: (1) obs.monster.is_edible via items.get_monster_meat_info() (returns None for undead / constructs / oozes / fungi etc). (2) Starvation gate lifted hunger<=15 -> hunger<=30 so the override fires while the agent still has HP cushion to win a fight. (3) Vendor food stockpile target 5 -> 8 to buy harder before starvation hits. (4) In combat_mode + starving + inedible monster -> flee immediately. Skip the threat-flee check when starving + edible -- we need to win that fight to eat. Smoke (30 runs, 2000 turns): max floor jumped to 7 for elf + dwarf (was 5 / 6), mean floor up across all races, dwarf mean turns 917 -> 1002. Same death count as last batch -- honest deaths still happen, just no more wasted-fight starvations.",
    "Smart playtest policy: starvation override + bigger food stockpile. Fresh 30-run playtest at 2000 turns showed 7 of 30 runs ending alive at HP=1 with hunger=0 -- the weakness gate (AVOID monsters at HP<50%) was making dying agents MORE timid, trapping them in slow-motion starvation pinning for 1500+ turns alive but doomed. Two fixes in wizardscavern/playtest_harness.py: (1) vendor food stockpile target 2 -> 5 so a shop visit stocks ~15 nutrition uses (3 per Rations stack) instead of ~6. (2) When hunger <= 15 AND no food in bag, drop M from AVOID -- the agent now engages monsters for meat drops as a last-resort food source. Warps stay avoided. Smoke (30 runs, 2000 turns): zero starve-pinned runs across all races (was 7/30). Deaths up correspondingly (elf 8->9, human 5->8, dwarf 5->7) because previously-doomed runs now die honestly instead of zombie-surviving the budget. Mean turn count down for the same reason -- artificial-long tails removed. This is healthier data than the prior censoring.",
    "Smart playtest policy: stuck-on-floor escape hatches. Discovered after the dwarf buff that dwarves at 60-84 HP could survive long enough to camp floor 1 for the full 5000-turn budget when they couldn't find the downstairs. Root cause: the wayfinder + lantern + random walk were locally trapping the agent in a 38-tile subregion of a 108-tile floor, never discovering the D tile. Four coordinated escape hatches (all in wizardscavern/playtest_harness.py): (1) PlaytestSession tracks `floor_arrival_turn` per descend, exposed via obs.turns_on_floor. (2) When turns_on_floor > 300 the clear-before-descend gate drops -- the agent will descend even with unvisited beneficials remaining, since an unreachable beneficial behind a wall the greedy walker can't navigate around is no better than no beneficial at all. (3) warp_mode now accepts the warp ('n') when turns_on_floor > 200 instead of always resisting -- empirical floor layouts (verified on seed 7) have regions connected only via warps, so the always-resist policy was the lock. (4) Random walk fallback biases toward undiscovered (fog-of-war None) neighbours before falling back to any walkable direction. (5) Lantern fires more aggressively when stuck: periodic every 10 turns when turns_on_floor > 200, even when all four cardinal neighbours are already known -- the radius-7 cross still reveals up to 28 farther-out cells past the immediate region. Smoke (30-run grid, 1500 turns): max floor 8 reached on elf seed 10 alive at T1500. Mean floor up across all races. Some seeds still corner-trap because the greedy walker has no pathfinder -- worth a future BFS pass.",
    "Dwarf buff: race HP routes through base_max_health_bonus + Battleaxe starter weapon. Death-cause analysis flagged dwarves as the worst-surviving race (7/10 deaths, mean 700 turns vs elf 1019 / human 924). Root cause: the dwarf race health_mod=+20 added to stats['health'] at character creation, but max_health is `level*10 + strength*2 + base_max_health_bonus` -- the race +HP got clamped right back at the formula max (Lv1 dwarf with STR 12 capped at 34 HP regardless). Two coordinated changes: (1) Dwarf health_mod +20 -> +30 in both game_systems.py:3455 and the harness RACE_MODS table. (2) game_systems.py character-creation now routes POSITIVE race health_mod through `pc.base_max_health_bonus`, so the +30 actually raises max_health (Lv1 dwarf now 60/64 vs previous 30/34). Negative mods (elf -10) still go to starting-HP only, preserving the squishy-elf flavor. (3) Race-aware starter weapon: dwarf gets a Battleaxe (atk+4) instead of the Dagger (atk+2) -- same Lv0 / value 25 so equip + repair cost stay reasonable. Vendor(starting=True) at vendor.py:93 and the harness starter pack both swap on race. Re-run: dwarf deaths 7/10 -> 5/10 (parity with elf/human), mean turns 700 -> 837, max floor 5 -> 7 (deepest in the grid).",
    "Death-cause-driven balance pass. 30-run analysis of why playtesters die surfaced two patterns: (1) 9/16 deaths to Lv5+ Undead Guardians (UNDEAD WRAITH Lv5, DRAGON LICH Lv7-8) spawning next to tombs on floors 1-6 with 40-58 HP killing-blows that one-shot fresh characters; (2) 11/16 deaths held UNUSED healing potions because the in-combat drink gate fired too late. Two coordinated fixes: (a) game_systems.py:2611 -- the undead-guardian spawn at adjacent tomb monster rooms had a +1 level boost on top of the pool's natural max, leaking an extra level above the player's floor. Now clamped via `min(template_level + 1, player.z + 2)`. Re-run: Wraiths dropped Lv5 -> Lv4, Liches Lv7-8 -> Lv6, killing-blows >40 HP down from 9/16 to 5/16. (b) playtest_harness.py smart policy: pre-emptive potion drink in game_loop when adjacent neighbour is M (monster), HP < 80%, and a healing potion is in the bag -- catches the 'init-loss one-shot' scenario where the agent went 100% -> 5% in a single monster turn, past the in-combat trigger. Also raised the in-combat potion gate from HP<30% to HP<50% so the agent reaches for potions before the lethal blow lands.",
    "Smart playtest policy: equipment evaluation. obs.inventory[*] now exposes attack_bonus / defense_bonus / item_level / equipped flag on weapons + armor, mirrored on obs.player.equipped. Smart policy gains a _best_upgrade helper that scans the bag for a non-cursed non-sealed weapon/armor with strictly higher attack_bonus / defense_bonus than the slotted piece. When found, game_loop pops inventory and the inventory branch sends e<N> to equip. Skips items the agent KNOWS are cursed (buc_known=True AND buc_status='cursed') because cursed gear welds to the hand; unidentified items remain eligible (that's the upgrade gamble the economy is built around). Smoke (30-run grid at 1500 turns): elf reached floor 6 for the first time, dwarf reached floor 6 (was 4). Survival count steady at 14/30 -- agents push deeper into harder content rather than dying less. Verified end to end: Steel Sword (atk+10) auto-equips over Dagger (atk+2); a known-cursed Doom Blade (atk+15) is correctly ignored.",
    "Playtest log + LOTR names + vendor identify. Three QoL changes on the playtest harness: (1) Default name=\"Tester\" now picks a seed-stable LOTR-flavoured name from a per-race pool -- elves get Galadriel/Legolas/Glorfindel/Tauriel/etc., dwarves Thorin/Balin/Durin/Bombur, men Aragorn/Theoden/Faramir/Eowyn. Makes transcripts read like adventurer logs instead of T200 spreadsheets. (2) Smart policy at vendor_shop now identifies unknown scrolls + potions via id<N> after the buy/repair phase (skipping when gold drops below a 100g budget floor) -- upgrade scrolls are the high-value drop the user explicitly called out and you can't use one without knowing what it is. Equipment identify costs 2x and is skipped (gear ID's by use anyway). Scroll gets its own category tag in _item_category. (3) Per-run summary line auto-appended to playtest_runs.log at the repo root (gitignored, override via WIZARDSCAVERN_PLAYTEST_LOG env var). Format: ISO timestamp + seed + race + LOTR name + policy + turns + floor + hp + gold + alive + final mode. Useful for tail -f during smoke runs and post-hoc analysis. Smoke (15-run grid): names + log lines land; identify path verified end-to-end via direct test (Yumthus the Wise's Scroll, 25g L0 cost).",
    "Smart playtest policy: garden + library + blacksmith + shrine. Four more special-room interactions wired up so the playtester actually USES rooms it walks onto instead of escaping with 'back'. Garden mode (+fey_garden_mode) -> 'h' to harvest (food + crafting ingredients; fey gardens are ephemeral so always grab). Library mode -> 'r' to search; if the handler bumps us into library_read_decision_mode it gets 'y' to attempt the read (success teaches a spell or gives XP). Blacksmith -> '1' to repair weapon, '2' to repair armor when the equipped piece is sub-100% durability and not sealed (cheaper than vendors at 80% rate); if neither needs repair the policy steps off via n/s/e/w. Shrine of the Fallen -> 'p' to pray for a one-shot stat/HP boost (shrine_used flag makes this one-and-done). Smoke (15-run grid): floor 6 reached for the first time (elf seed 123, dies on the very last turn), floor 5 cleared alive (human seed 123 ends at 30/30 + 925g), 10+ garden harvests + 8 library read-attempts + 2 shrine prays. Zero crashes.",
    "Smart playtest policy: tomb raiding + dungeon key tracking + better random walk. Agent now prays at tombs ('p') when weak (safe heal) and raids them ('r') when healthy (risky big reward); the visited-features tracker prevents re-raiding the same tomb. Dungeon flow: obs.dungeon_keys exposes the (x,y,z) tuples gs.dungeon_keys (populated when a key-holding monster dies, combat.py:515); obs.keyed_dungeon_target points the distant wayfinder at the nearest unlooted dungeon we hold a key for (filters gs.looted_dungeons so we don't ping-pong on a raided dungeon). step() dispatches tomb_mode + dungeon_mode + dungeon_unlocked_mode through the canonical handlers. Smart policy at dungeon_mode unconditionally sends 'u' -- handler unlocks if keyed, otherwise logs 'no key' and flips back to game_loop (room_actions.py:1914), so we never get stuck mid-interaction. Random-walk fallback now refuses to re-step onto an already-visited feature tile (C/G/L/O/A/P/T/N/V), so unkeyed dungeons aren't a stationary trap any more. Smoke (15-run grid): survival 14/15 (was 11/15), 3 dungeons unlocked + raided (human_42, dwarf_42, dwarf_2024), floor 3 reached on 5 seeds, elf seed 42 ends at HP 40/40 -- altar pray + pool drink stacking max-HP boons on top of the 28-base.",
    "Playtest agent gets cardinal lantern + threat-aware flee + altar/pool interaction + BUC obs. Game change: Lantern.use in items.py:2596 and room_actions.py:3592 now reveals along the four cardinal axes only (N/S/E/W up to light_radius + upgrade_level tiles, stopping at walls per-axis). Previously revealed a Euclidean disc which leaked light around walls through diagonal gaps and didn't match the in-game minimap. Harness adds: obs.inventory[*] surfaces buc_status / buc_known / is_sealed / is_identified for weapons + armor (and is_identified for everything else), so the policy can avoid blindly equipping cursed gear once detected; obs.player.equipped mirrors the same fields. Smart policy gains threat assessment in combat_mode: monster_too_tough if m.level > pc.level + 2 OR m.max_hp > 2 * pc.max_hp -> flee. Also pops inventory at HP<30% with a healing potion but no affordable Heal spell -- earlier playtest pass had elves dying with 4 untouched potions because the combat heal logic was mana-only. step() dispatches altar_mode and pool_mode through their handlers; policy returns 'pray' at altars (claims the god's current tier reward) and 'dr' at pools (drinks for RNG boon/poison). Prior playtest data: 10 of 19 warp resists actually failed -- failed resists usually push the agent up 1-3 floors, so the floor-5 records from the previous pass were partly warp-luck not pure clear-by-clear progression",
    "Smart playtest policy: fog of war + real lantern + weakness model + clear-before-descend. (1) obs.neighbors and obs.nearest_features now respect room.discovered (default-on; --no-fog disables) so the agent has to actually walk through tiles or light up to see the floor. (2) Lantern.use in items.py:2596 and room_actions.py:3592 now uses `light_radius + upgrade_level` for the reveal radius -- previously hardcoded as `upgrade_level + 1`, leaving the starter lantern (level 0) at radius 1, useless. Starter now reveals a 7-tile circle, one light per ~12 moves of planning. (3) Smart policy gains is_weak gate (HP<50% or broken weapon/armor) and skips M (monster) and W (warp) neighbours in the wayfinder when weak. (4) Wayfinder priority is now context-sensitive: beneficials (C/G/L/O/A/P) precede D so the agent clears each floor before descending. (5) stairs_down_mode handler now refuses 'd' when any unvisited beneficial remains on the floor -- steps off and resumes the floor sweep. (6) New warp_mode dispatch in step(); policy always returns 'y' (resist) -- a random teleport into the deep is rarely a survival win. Smoke (15-run grid): floor 5 reached twice (human 2024, dwarf 999) -- previous record was floor 4, once. Survival 14/15 with the one death being legitimate combat, not a stuck loop. Avg lantern uses dropped 17/run -> 4/run (productive, not vanity). Final gold totals up ~50% as agents collect more loot per floor.",
    "Spell-drop bug fix in items.py:3039 (drop_monster_items). When a monster rolled a Spell drop, the cloning call passed effect_magnitude / value / element kwargs that Spell.__init__ doesn't accept -- and `base.effect_magnitude` didn't exist on the template either, so the call raised AttributeError before the item was constructed and the drop was silently lost. Surfaced by the smart playtest agent on dwarf seed 999 turn 140; the agent now survives long enough to provoke spell drops. Fix: clone all Spell fields explicitly from the template using the canonical signature at items.py:3418.",
    "Lantern A/B in the smart playtest policy. Adds `'l'` to the game_loop handler in step() (routes to process_lantern_quick_use, no game-turn tick), exposes obs.player.lantern with fuel/spare_fuel_uses/upgrade_level, and gives smart_policy a periodic lantern light (every 8th turn while fuel > 5) plus a Lantern Fuel stockpile rule for vendors (target 2 uses when current fuel < 20). Default-on with --no-lantern for A/B testing. Local 5-seed comparison shows IDENTICAL survival, max floor, final HP, and final gold with vs without lantern use -- because the harness's obs.neighbors / obs.nearest_features ignore the room's `discovered` flag, so the agent already peers through fog-of-war and the lantern's tile-reveal mechanic doesn't add anything for it. The lantern's `light_radius` parameter at items.py:2574 is also unused -- the actual reveal radius is `upgrade_level + 1`, so the starter lantern reveals 1 tile in each direction. Worth either upgrading the mechanic or accepting it as flavor.",
    "Smart playtest policy: starter pack, fresh-meat eating, vendor repairs. new_game() now ships a starter pack by default (Dagger + Leather Armor equipped, Lantern, 3 Rations, 4 Minor Healing Potions, 290g left over) -- mirrors what the in-game starting_shop hands out, so the agent isn't punching monsters bare-fisted. Drops in via --no-starter-pack if you want bare-fisted runs. obs.inventory now surfaces durability / max_durability / is_broken on weapons and armor, plus rot_timer / is_cooked / is_rotten on Meat. obs.player.equipped reports the same durability info for the slotted weapon + armor (which is also why the starter pack adds them to inventory.items AND the equipment slots -- the vendor repair handler indexes off inventory, see vendor.py:733). Smart policy gains: eat-fresh-meat priority (urgent at rot_timer <= 8 turns regardless of hunger, so kill drops aren't wasted), broken-gear swap (opens inventory and equips the spare when the slotted weapon/armor breaks and a spare of the same kind is in the bag), and vendor repair (issues r<N> for damaged equipped gear at <40% durability before the buy phase). Smoke (15-run grid): survival jumps from 8/15 to 14/15, floor reach from 4/15-at-2 to 11/15-at-2 plus 3 hitting floor 3 and a dwarf seed 999 reaching floor 4. Confirmed meat-eat (2/2 drops consumed) and vendor repair (27g r1 + healing-potion restock on human seed 123)",
    "Smart playtest policy gains a wayfinder. The previous random-policy-with-priority-gates never reached floor 2 or visited a vendor across 30 runs because random walking dies before bumping into features. Three additions in wizardscavern/playtest_harness.py: (1) neighbors[N/S/E/W] in obs reports the cardinal room types ignoring the discovered flag (it's a tester, not a player); (2) nearest_features[D|V|C] reports the (dx,dy) vector to the closest unvisited target tile on the floor; (3) visited_features set in PlaytestSession tracks every non-trivial tile we've stepped onto so the wayfinder doesn't oscillate between an altar and an empty neighbour. The smart_policy now prefers an adjacent unvisited feature tile (priority D > V > C > A > T > N > P > L > G > O, U deliberately omitted -- ascending wastes turns), and falls back to a greedy step toward the nearest distant D or V. Vendor jumps ahead of stairs when healing potions < 2 and gold >= 50. Also loosened the in-combat heal gate from hp<40% -> hp<55% so the heal cast actually fires before the player dies crossing the threshold. Smoke: smart-elf seed 999 now visits a vendor, buys 5 healing potions, reaches floor 2",
]
